g.text: Single leader model - one main node responsible for coordinating all activities
High availability but vertical scaling to meet growing demands
- can handle massive volumes of workflows and jobs
- support various user types - engineer, data scientist, business analysts, content producers
- Managing workflow definitions, including versioning and metadata.
- Executing workflows by managing step instances, which are the runtime versions of each step.
- Supporting advanced data patterns like foreach loops, conditional branches, and subworkflows.
- Allowing steps to be reused across workflows through step templates.
- Enabling dynamic workflows by supporting code-based parameter injection through a secure custom expression
- Providing a timeline view of workflow state changes to help with debugging and tracking.
- to define when a workflow runs
- exact once execution - at least once + deduplication to avoid duplicate runs
- Responds to internal or external events. Internal e.g. workflow events. External e.g. S3 events
- can trigger an entire workflow execution or a step execution as well
- distributed queues for messaging across components
- CockroachDB for workflow and step data. Strong consistency guarantees + high availability
- provision to handle massive no. of steps in a workflow - nested foreach loops
Execution abstractions to support wide user types
- Standard step types -- represent standard operations like spark
job, SQL query, moving data from db to spreadsheet
- DSL interface to manage workflows - supporting yaml,
- parameterised workflow to support dynamic adaptation
Aggregated views and rollup - high level summary of workflow success/failures
